{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476843"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13957"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13957"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.1,0.18,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13957"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35430"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2053"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44719"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department with a history of being found submerged in a backyard pool. He had been missing for approximately 10 minutes before being discovered. Bystander cardiopulmonary resuscitation was initiated immediately. On arrival, he appears critically unwell. His pulse rate is 0/min, blood pressure is unrecordable, respiratory rate is 0/min, and his core temperature is 30\u00b0C. He is in asystolic cardiac arrest. He has been intubated en route, and intravenous access has been established. The total duration of asystole is estimated to be no more than 20 minutes based on the history provided. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform immediate defibrillation","Administer intravenous amiodarone","Declare the patient deceased","Administer high-dose intravenous adrenaline","Continue cardiopulmonary resuscitation and initiate rewarming"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinue cardiopulmonary resuscitation and initiate rewarming\u003C/strong\u003E. This child has suffered a drowning event complicated by severe hypothermia and cardiac arrest. In paediatric patients with hypothermia and cardiac arrest, especially in the context of drowning, the adage \u0022nobody is dead until warm and dead\u0022 applies. Aggressive resuscitation efforts should continue until the patient is rewarmed to near-normal body temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeclaring the patient deceased\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature in this situation. Despite the duration of asystole, the severe hypothermia may be providing a degree of neuroprotection, and there are case reports of good neurological outcomes in similar scenarios with prolonged resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario. Amiodarone is used for the treatment of ventricular fibrillation or pulseless ventricular tachycardia resistant to defibrillation, not for asystole. Moreover, in severe hypothermia, the effectiveness of antiarrhythmic drugs is reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming immediate defibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the patient is in asystole, not a shockable rhythm. Defibrillation is only indicated for ventricular fibrillation or pulseless ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering high-dose intravenous adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in severe hypothermia. The hypothermic heart may be less responsive to medications, and standard doses of resuscitation drugs should be used once rewarming has commenced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe priority in this case is to continue cardiopulmonary resuscitation while simultaneously rewarming the patient. Rewarming methods might include warm intravenous fluids, warm humidified oxygen, and external warming measures. In some centres, extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) might be considered for rewarming in severe cases. Core temperature should be continuously monitored during the resuscitation and rewarming process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In paediatric drowning with hypothermia and cardiac arrest, aggressive resuscitation should be continued until the patient is rewarmed.","Core temperature should be monitored in hypothermic patients.","Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) is a consideration in severe hypothermia with cardiac arrest."],"references":["Orlowski JP, Szpilman D. Drowning (submersion injuries). In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/drowning-submersion-injuries?search=drowning%20resusitation\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Pellegrino F, Raffaldi I, Rossi R, De Vito B, Pagano M, Garelli D, Bondone C. Epidemiology, clinical aspects, and management of pediatric drowning. Ital J Pediatr. 2023 Jun 14;49(1):74. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10268379/","Raess L, Darms A, Meyer-Heim A. Drowning in Children: Retrospective Analysis of Incident Characteristics, Predicting Parameters, and Long-Term Outcome. Children (Basel). 2020 Jul 1;7(7):70. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7401877/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35430"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13957"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35430"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-07T19:20:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-07T19:22:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"em